times against each other. Demonstrating the previously unrecognized extent to which nonelites participated in the formation of our ideas about politics, manners, and gender and race relations, A Nation of Speechifiers provides an unparalleled genealogy of early American identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aNationalismxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aNationalismxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aNationalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aNationalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aOratoryxSocial aspectsxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aOratoryxSocial aspectsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aOratoryxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aOratoryxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  anation, revolution, colonial america, history, politics, speech, politicians, nonfiction, nationhood, belonging, identity, public, community, elocution, education, debate, race, gender, press, nationalism, oratory, democracy, women, feminism, virtue, printing, benjamin franklin, schools, clubs, media, social mobility, participation, sensibility, manners.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022618019940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226180212423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226180212/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles